1
00:00:00,858 --> 00:00:20,672
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa

2
00:00:22,745 --> 00:00:39,304
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:42,027 --> 00:00:48,414
The first thing we need to do when we start on a course is to make sure that we have the right intentions.

4
00:00:50,031 --> 00:00:54,970
If we have the wrong intentions, the practice will be skewed and we'll just end up disappointed.

5
00:00:56,195 --> 00:01:00,732
So we need to ask ourselves why we've come on a course of meditation.

6
00:01:02,283 --> 00:01:12,259
Now it's only fair to think that it's going to bring some sort of physical and psychological benefit, some sort of clarification of our thought, and some spiritual benefit.

7
00:01:13,521 --> 00:01:28,965
But if we make these objectives our moment-to-moment aims, then we'll simply get into that old grasping, getting, attaining mindset, and end up all frustrated and go away swearing we'll never waste our time doing something so useless again.

8
00:01:29,957 --> 00:01:30,379
Why?

9
00:01:31,180 --> 00:01:34,927
Because the self brings into any equation a distortion, a projection.

10
00:01:36,609 --> 00:01:46,126
Remember, it is the self itself which is the delusion, and if we allow its ambitions to guide us, it really will be a case of the blind leading the blind.

11
00:01:47,811 --> 00:02:01,430
So ultimate objectives, the purification of the heart from all self-driven desire and the realization of nibbana, are beyond the capability of self, beyond the capability of self-will.

12
00:02:02,611 --> 00:02:07,778
And as we progress in the course, the reasons for this should become apparent, I hope.

13
00:02:09,022 --> 00:02:24,264
For instance, many of you will have heard of the vipassana jnana, the spiritual insights, of the four stages of sainthood, which lead to the awakening, of the arahat, of course, the enlightened person, and nibbana.

14
00:02:25,408 --> 00:02:33,003
It's impossible, I think, to come onto a course of this nature and not have some such ideas of attainment floating about in the mind.

15
00:02:34,265 --> 00:02:35,388
Well, let them float.

16
00:02:36,129 --> 00:02:37,132
Don't hang on to them.

17
00:02:37,953 --> 00:02:45,949
Because for sure, such desires are definitely beyond the self, for such attainments transcend the self itself.

18
00:02:47,549 --> 00:02:54,276
Worse still, if we have some idea as to what spiritual attainments are, then only two things can happen.

19
00:02:55,638 --> 00:03:01,966
Either we won't attain what we've conceived and be disappointed, or worse we will and be utterly deluded.

20
00:03:03,448 --> 00:03:11,116
For whatever spiritual insights are, they are not expressions of our concepts, our thoughts, our imaginings.

21
00:03:12,437 --> 00:03:17,403
They are direct experiences beyond the capability of the mind to imagine.

22
00:03:18,143 --> 00:03:29,919
Indeed, all we do when we attain our concepts is to make manifest in the material world what we had imagined, just as a designer might finally get their dream car built.

23
00:03:31,381 --> 00:03:35,447
But cars, houses, jewellery are all of this phenomenal world.

24
00:03:36,709 --> 00:03:38,270
Our sights are aimed a little higher.

25
00:03:38,812 --> 00:03:43,998
Indeed, they are aimed at the supramundane world, beyond the phenomenal world.

26
00:03:47,336 --> 00:03:56,306
Now so committed are we to these ideas that sometimes, when something strange or wonderful begins to happen in our meditation, we'll suddenly grasp onto it.

27
00:03:56,947 --> 00:03:59,049
This is it, this is it, and we're all bated breath.

28
00:04:00,290 --> 00:04:01,072
Hoping to attain.

29
00:04:01,111 --> 00:04:03,133
Now that's a very misleading word.

30
00:04:04,094 --> 00:04:07,337
The better word, if there can ever be a word, is to realise.

31
00:04:08,278 --> 00:04:10,020
Suddenly there's a seeing, and that's it.

32
00:04:10,581 --> 00:04:10,981
Insight.

33
00:04:12,262 --> 00:04:18,057
And the only way we're going to realize an insight is, paradoxically, to get out of the way.

34
00:04:21,386 --> 00:04:23,892
It's a bit like working out a mathematical problem.

35
00:04:24,896 --> 00:04:26,119
Take Archimedes.

36
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:30,805
Now the king had asked him to prove that the crown was pure gold.

37
00:04:32,226 --> 00:04:35,130
To make sure, he had to get the specific gravity.

38
00:04:35,791 --> 00:04:43,040
And to get that, no doubt you remember your maths, you need to know the weight and volume of a given object.

39
00:04:44,744 --> 00:04:50,951
Now getting the weight was easy, but how to get the volume of an irregular shape?

40
00:04:50,971 --> 00:04:51,853
A real koan.

41
00:04:53,369 --> 00:04:55,911
He had given up and went to relax in the bath.

42
00:04:56,653 --> 00:04:57,112
Where else?

43
00:04:57,934 --> 00:04:59,975
And right there, Eureka!

44
00:04:59,995 --> 00:05:00,877
I found it, I got it!

45
00:05:02,459 --> 00:05:09,987
As his body slipped into the water, he saw that the amount of water rising was equal to the volume of his irregular-shaped body.

46
00:05:10,809 --> 00:05:16,574
Just then, when he was not thinking about it at all, when Archimedes was no longer in the wake,

47
00:05:17,821 --> 00:05:20,064
I think this sort of thing happens to us all the time.

48
00:05:20,985 --> 00:05:24,408
Sometimes we even sleep on a problem and wake up with the answer.

49
00:05:25,569 --> 00:05:28,033
There's some intelligence there which doesn't think.

50
00:05:28,894 --> 00:05:30,475
It just perceives directly.

51
00:05:31,637 --> 00:05:33,860
It realizes something just like that.

52
00:05:35,401 --> 00:05:44,773
Well, that's the very same faculty that sees the way things really are and brings about the liberation from our delusions and consequent sufferings.

53
00:05:46,052 --> 00:05:58,096
So the truth of the matter is, we have to get out of the way, get out of the way completely and let paññā, that wonderful intuitive intelligence within us, do the work.

54
00:05:59,538 --> 00:06:06,593
We have to have faith in this higher power, a higher power within us to set us free from our delusions.

55
00:06:07,939 --> 00:06:11,084
The fact is that the truth is always there to be seen.

56
00:06:11,144 --> 00:06:17,350
It's more like looking into a dark room and suddenly the light goes on and we see everything.

57
00:06:18,291 --> 00:06:19,112
Just like that.

58
00:06:20,834 --> 00:06:23,137
Now the light didn't create the objects in the room.

59
00:06:23,156 --> 00:06:26,420
They were always there, always there to be seen.

60
00:06:27,281 --> 00:06:30,185
So the question is, how do we turn this light on?

61
00:06:30,886 --> 00:06:32,968
That's definitely THE question.

62
00:06:34,973 --> 00:06:51,053
Well, the first thing is to be absolutely clear that we can't make physical, psychological, intellectual and certainly not spiritual aims the purpose of our meditation course because that's all self-desire, self-driven ambition.

63
00:06:52,435 --> 00:06:57,701
What then can we make a legitimate aim and thereby not end up disillusioned?

64
00:06:58,783 --> 00:07:03,850
Well, that aim is simply and solely to develop the skills of meditation.

65
00:07:05,500 --> 00:07:29,009
And the reason for this is that all skills involved in Vipassana training, whatever these skills may be, and they differ from school to school, are concerned with lifting consciousness out of its embeddedness, its confusion with the body, heart and mind, and to make those very areas of experience the object of consciousness itself.

66
00:07:30,255 --> 00:07:50,103
In other words, all skills are there so that this intuitive consciousness, satipanya, that which knows, can see and understand exactly what the body, with all its sensations, the heart, with all its feelings, and the mind, with all its thoughts, actually are.

67
00:07:51,281 --> 00:08:01,177
It is a process of investigation by way of direct experience and this can't be done without consciousness lifting itself to a higher ground.

68
00:08:03,480 --> 00:08:09,869
You'll already be familiar with my favourite metaphor of the ornithologist from the Vipassana tape.

69
00:08:09,889 --> 00:08:18,521
To study birds, indeed any wildlife, the scientist has to be hidden from them so that their presence doesn't distort the creature's natural behaviour.

70
00:08:19,649 --> 00:08:21,831
And just by watching, they come to know.

71
00:08:22,331 --> 00:08:23,454
Just watching.

72
00:08:25,235 --> 00:08:31,202
Another image is to be up on the crow's nest of a ship, able to see what's happening on the ship and far beyond.

73
00:08:32,784 --> 00:08:39,192
And consider how our vision of planet Earth changed once we got those pictures from the moon.

74
00:08:40,014 --> 00:08:43,057
Suddenly, everybody's talking about the global village.

75
00:08:44,539 --> 00:08:51,231
we have to discover a similar vantage point within ourselves and once discovered, then the work truly begins.

76
00:08:51,712 --> 00:08:54,677
The work, the labour to maintain it.

77
00:08:56,280 --> 00:09:00,067
All of this will be down to the skilful means we employ.

78
00:09:03,355 --> 00:09:08,921
Now the Buddha was brought up in the Kshatriya caste, the warrior caste.

79
00:09:08,941 --> 00:09:12,664
So he would have been well acquainted with the needs and demands of skills training.

80
00:09:13,647 --> 00:09:18,172
He'd have practiced archery, wrestling, and he probably learned how to play an instrument.

81
00:09:19,452 --> 00:09:23,457
He would have known the need to repeat the same action over and over again.

82
00:09:24,259 --> 00:09:25,820
Practice makes perfect.

83
00:09:27,241 --> 00:09:31,826
How many times do world-class tennis players practice serving backhands and volleys

84
00:09:32,988 --> 00:09:43,774
So when Siddhartha Gautama set off on his spiritual quest to find the end of suffering, it's no wonder he sought out teachers who would show him how, the techniques of meditation.

85
00:09:45,221 --> 00:09:49,890
And the two teachers who helped him showed him how to attain all the blissful absorptions.

86
00:09:51,133 --> 00:09:55,522
But as we know, he wasn't satisfied with that, and that's when he went off on his own.

87
00:09:56,943 --> 00:10:05,660
And part of his greatness lies in the fact that he treads new territory and finds the solution to the great and overwhelming problem of human suffering.

88
00:10:07,345 --> 00:10:11,110
In the same way, we ourselves need to become spiritual athletes.

89
00:10:12,091 --> 00:10:15,658
To become athletes demands constant devotion to the practice of skills.

90
00:10:16,918 --> 00:10:19,342
We can't stop until we're fully enlightened.

91
00:10:20,504 --> 00:10:28,356
So it's best to cultivate an attitude that the training period for the spiritual gold medal is going to take a long time.

92
00:10:29,437 --> 00:10:33,825
So let's start right now, little by little.

93
00:10:33,804 --> 00:10:37,568
OK, sometimes we take time off, sometimes we just forget.

94
00:10:38,328 --> 00:10:46,397
Well, that's all right, so long as we acknowledge that we'll have fallen back a bit and that it's going to take a little special effort to get us back on track.

95
00:10:49,480 --> 00:10:52,663
Now, all skills training has to be self-reflective.

96
00:10:54,065 --> 00:11:01,111
We must in time be fully aware of what the skills are, why we're using them, when we should use them and so on.

97
00:11:02,071 --> 00:11:08,038
And we should know them so well that we can eventually guide ourselves and make teachers redundant.

98
00:11:09,660 --> 00:11:13,966
This is achieved not simply by practicing the techniques but also by reflecting on them.

99
00:11:14,908 --> 00:11:26,745
Practicing the techniques and becoming aware of the feedback and becoming more and more aware of what the techniques are trying to help us do and how we can use them more and more skillfully.

100
00:11:28,750 --> 00:11:32,884
All this focus on skills training, however, can lead to one big mistake.

101
00:11:33,989 --> 00:11:40,532
And I want to warn you right now, right at the beginning, because it's so important not to have this wrong understanding.

102
00:11:42,351 --> 00:11:46,360
We can become so involved in technique that we can't see the wood for the trees.

103
00:11:47,342 --> 00:11:52,394
Worse, we actually begin to believe that the technique is what really achieves the insight.

104
00:11:53,255 --> 00:12:00,731
The technique becomes a sort of mystique, a sacred ritual which has to be performed exactly right or nothing will be gained.

105
00:12:00,711 --> 00:12:13,083
Meditators become entirely wrapped up in the details and cordon off their retreat from others, saying it's the best or the pristine or quicker or even, so I've heard, more modern.

106
00:12:14,802 --> 00:12:33,604
What we can say is that every valid system of vipassana has its own built-in logic, checks and balances, and that ultimately a person centres on a particular technique for a variety of reasons, such as their personality, their relationship with the teacher, the availability of courses, and so on.

107
00:12:35,102 --> 00:12:49,865
When this mistake of mystifying a technique is made the reason is that the aim of the techniques has been lost and the aim is simply to get that consciousness of ours onto a steady position of inward observation.

108
00:12:50,927 --> 00:12:54,393
Once that is done we can let go of all technique.

109
00:12:57,118 --> 00:12:58,038
Having said that

110
00:12:58,356 --> 00:13:00,940
Don't think that you can drop the technique within a week.

111
00:13:01,880 --> 00:13:05,504
Surely there'll be moments, minutes perhaps, when we can just observe.

112
00:13:06,264 --> 00:13:09,508
But then as soon as we lose it, we need to get back to the technique.

113
00:13:10,729 --> 00:13:15,934
The whole point then of the skills of meditation is to take us beyond themselves.

114
00:13:16,695 --> 00:13:20,899
They're part of the raft the Buddha talked about that takes us to the other shore.

115
00:13:21,759 --> 00:13:27,485
Once we've arrived, there'll be no need to carry it about, no need to carry the raft on our backs.

116
00:13:30,048 --> 00:13:43,381
So the purpose then of all technique is to raise consciousness to a level where it can observe quite impartially the goings on of the body with all its sensations from the sense bases and all its feelings

117
00:13:44,307 --> 00:13:50,418
the heart with all its varied moods and emotions, and the mind with all its teeming thoughts and imaginings.

118
00:13:51,520 --> 00:14:01,640
Just to be able to sit back and watch, as if at a cinema, just watching the film on the screen, the screen of cognition, our cognitive faculty.

119
00:14:02,751 --> 00:14:09,951
In this way we begin to taste the unconditioned consciousness that the Buddha exclaimed he had attained upon enlightenment.

120
00:14:11,014 --> 00:14:18,634
That's part of the verses we chant in the morning, the celebration of his liberation from suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

121
00:14:22,072 --> 00:14:24,937
Now as time passes, the teaching becomes dulled.

122
00:14:25,738 --> 00:14:30,785
It's been over two and a half thousand years now since the teachings were first expounded.

123
00:14:31,787 --> 00:14:40,539
But there are always reformation movements throughout the history of Buddhism, some large and some small, which revitalize the teachings, the Dharma.

124
00:14:41,942 --> 00:14:51,777
And the Mahasi Sayadaw must be accredited as one of the key teachers, if not the main influence, in revitalizing the practice of vipassana in Theravada Buddhist countries.

125
00:14:53,663 --> 00:15:01,635
The Mahasi had been teaching in the north of Burma when some people went looking for a teacher to start a meditation centre in Rangoon.

126
00:15:02,537 --> 00:15:13,173
Please note this was lay-led and the special quality of a Mahasi centre is that there are always lay teachers and the majority of the centres are within the city or town boundaries.

127
00:15:14,621 --> 00:15:23,114
This in itself, it seems, was a revolution, since up until then it was generally presumed that only monastics could gain anything from meditation.

128
00:15:24,174 --> 00:15:25,636
In fact, the lie goes deeper.

129
00:15:26,298 --> 00:15:38,975
It is still propagated by some, and some high-ranking members of the monastic sangha, unfortunately, that no one can make any spiritual progress these days, let alone become enlightened, because of the corruption of the Buddha Dhamma.

130
00:15:40,475 --> 00:15:44,919
As far as I'm concerned, that may say more about them than the state of the Buddha Dhamma.

131
00:15:46,140 --> 00:15:53,969
The Mahasi developed a technique which has helped so many people to develop their spiritual lives and attain the noble paths and fruits.

132
00:15:56,892 --> 00:15:58,673
So what are these techniques he developed?

133
00:15:59,695 --> 00:16:03,339
The first of these techniques is to do with sitting meditation.

134
00:16:04,259 --> 00:16:10,025
Well, we've been through those on the tape you've just heard and you'll have noticed how detailed they are

135
00:16:10,850 --> 00:16:15,561
there's a direction given for any and every situation that might arise in the sitting posture.

136
00:16:18,375 --> 00:16:27,953
Again, there are directions for walking meditation, which progresses from walking as fast as you want for exercise, to walking as slowly as humanly possible.

137
00:16:29,275 --> 00:16:38,332
And when standing there are also clear instructions, though the ones I give, as far as the posture itself goes, are taken from the Chinese discipline of Qigong.

138
00:16:39,414 --> 00:16:41,599
But you can stand quite ordinarily if you want.

139
00:16:43,164 --> 00:16:49,797
And for other daily activities, such as eating, washing and lying down, there are equally direct instructions.

140
00:16:51,219 --> 00:16:55,506
But here I want to concentrate on why these different techniques are used.

141
00:16:57,610 --> 00:17:02,759
The first technique, that is, I believe, specific to the Mahasi method, is noting.

142
00:17:04,276 --> 00:17:15,210
Although it may be pointed out that if there's any thinking, it's not real vipassana, what is misunderstood here is that this is a technique to get a meditator beyond thinking.

143
00:17:16,171 --> 00:17:17,412
It's not an end in itself.

144
00:17:19,174 --> 00:17:25,962
According to the Buddha's teaching, there are two stages of concentrated thought before full concentration is established.

145
00:17:27,361 --> 00:17:30,365
The first is a simple noting or naming of the object.

146
00:17:31,508 --> 00:17:38,699
This simple thought, naming, noting, is known as vitaka and is likened to a bee flying towards a flower.

147
00:17:40,602 --> 00:17:43,467
A word which encapsulates the whole experience.

148
00:17:45,128 --> 00:17:47,333
In a child this is very obvious and simplistic.

149
00:17:48,153 --> 00:17:52,922
When a two-year-old is beginning to speak, they'll rejoice at being able to name an object.

150
00:17:53,321 --> 00:17:54,364
Ka, ka, ka.

151
00:17:55,896 --> 00:18:08,972
For that mind at that level of language, the word car simply points at the object, and there's not much thought around it, since language itself, which allows us to think about an object, is not developed enough for this to happen.

152
00:18:10,976 --> 00:18:15,761
But for us, the word car conjures up a host of memories and desires.

153
00:18:17,632 --> 00:18:22,957
This thinking about an object, this mentation, is known as papancha.

154
00:18:22,977 --> 00:18:24,818
Now there's a lovely word, papancha.

155
00:18:25,880 --> 00:18:27,000
It's proliferation.

156
00:18:27,681 --> 00:18:33,866
And the effect of this thinking and daydreaming is to keep us off the presenting object and distract the mind.

157
00:18:34,968 --> 00:18:38,750
The Buddha likened it to a monkey jumping from branch to branch.

158
00:18:40,252 --> 00:18:42,194
Now this is exactly what we've got to stop.

159
00:18:42,994 --> 00:18:46,018
We've got to stop the mind moving off the present moment.

160
00:18:47,415 --> 00:18:51,971
So shrinking thought down to a single word is the preliminary effort.

161
00:18:53,736 --> 00:18:59,855
But at this stage the meditator is forever having to pull the attention out of wandering and into watching.

162
00:19:01,387 --> 00:19:08,817
When we find ourselves complaining that the mind won't stay still, we fail to understand that this is exactly what the training is about.

163
00:19:09,498 --> 00:19:18,009
It's all about reconditioning the mind to be present, to be attentive to what's happening now, not to what it would like to happen.

164
00:19:19,852 --> 00:19:21,493
So this is the stage of vittaka.

165
00:19:22,295 --> 00:19:30,045
The meditator uses the noting word to limit the thinking mind and retrain the attention to rest upon the object.

166
00:19:32,134 --> 00:19:36,861
Now this noting has to be done with precise effort, a determined noting.

167
00:19:38,061 --> 00:19:44,128
Rising, falling, rising, falling.

168
00:19:45,891 --> 00:19:59,626
And although there is careful noting, the attention is not placed on the word itself, but on the experience, the feeling of a sensation, the sensation of an emotion, the knowing of a thought.

169
00:20:01,125 --> 00:20:05,330
Now thought can be split into two categories, a concept and an image.

170
00:20:06,732 --> 00:20:15,163
At the breath, for instance, as we note, there will be a concept of rising and falling, and also an image of the abdomen in the mind.

171
00:20:16,266 --> 00:20:23,595
We don't try to destroy them, we just keep pointing the attention at the feeling of movement, the sensations.

172
00:20:25,217 --> 00:20:30,423
And this attention will then grow in strength until thought cannot distract it.

173
00:20:31,635 --> 00:20:39,049
The meditator is still noting, but the attention, instead of wanting to wander off, becomes stuck, as it were, on the object.

174
00:20:40,452 --> 00:20:45,663
This is the second stage of developing right concentration and is called vichara.

175
00:20:46,744 --> 00:20:51,855
This is likened to a bee landing on and sucking the nectar of a flower.

176
00:20:54,333 --> 00:21:06,855
The meditator continues to note diligently, placing the attention more and more on the object, really feeling those sensations, really experiencing them as they arise and pass away.

177
00:21:08,378 --> 00:21:14,990
This unflagging effort will draw all the energy out of thought to a point where thought stops.

178
00:21:16,185 --> 00:21:19,490
Remember, thinking is always about something.

179
00:21:20,172 --> 00:21:21,914
It always comes after the event.

180
00:21:22,856 --> 00:21:27,644
So when thinking stops, that must mean we are right in the present moment.

181
00:21:28,967 --> 00:21:40,404
And it's at this point of bare knowing that the true vipassana consciousness, samasati, right awareness, arises and our intuitive intelligence, paññā,

182
00:21:40,384 --> 00:21:47,980
free from the distortion of thought and image, can finally begin to see the way things really are.

183
00:21:49,563 --> 00:21:53,210
So we don't have to worry about when to stop the noting.

184
00:21:53,471 --> 00:21:59,102
It will stop once we've arrived at a high enough level of awareness and concentration.

185
00:22:00,212 --> 00:22:09,944
These moments of pure vipassana are few and far between and very short in duration but they have great potential for insight.

186
00:22:11,066 --> 00:22:21,097
Such moments are known as kanika samadhi momentary concentration which lengthen into a moment to moment to moment concentrated awareness.

187
00:22:22,098 --> 00:22:28,026
And as we progress such moments of continual awareness lengthen and increase.

188
00:22:28,006 --> 00:22:29,750
It takes perseverance.

189
00:22:30,773 --> 00:22:31,576
So don't give up.

190
00:22:32,318 --> 00:22:36,330
When the going gets tough, the tough get going.

191
00:22:38,416 --> 00:22:42,910
Now when it comes to choosing a word, the simplest and most direct will do.

192
00:22:43,817 --> 00:22:50,109
And if a word doesn't come to mind, then any general word such as feeling, moving and so on will do.

193
00:22:50,130 --> 00:22:54,357
The word in itself is not all that important.

194
00:22:55,140 --> 00:22:58,906
Its purpose, remember, is to stop the mind wandering away.

195
00:23:00,372 --> 00:23:07,300
If we start looking for a word as a poet might, and we ask for a dictionary, well then we've definitely lost the plot.

196
00:23:08,582 --> 00:23:14,670
Sometimes strange stuff comes up and it's difficult to be precise, so any approximate word will do.

197
00:23:15,770 --> 00:23:22,278
Actually, when strange feelings do arise, the attention is so riveted that noting usually falls away anyway.

198
00:23:23,660 --> 00:23:33,491
Apart from noting in the basic postures of sitting, walking, standing and lying down, it's important to realize that we can't just limit our efforts to that.

199
00:23:34,853 --> 00:23:38,718
As the Mahasi pointed out, it's the continuity of awareness that brings success.

200
00:23:39,699 --> 00:23:43,083
You can't just stop, take a break or go for a short holiday.

201
00:23:43,824 --> 00:23:46,426
Spiritual practice is relentless.

202
00:23:47,790 --> 00:24:00,067
To make a good sustained effort in the sitting and then to get up and let the mind run around like a headless chicken is like blowing up a balloon and letting all the air out before you've tied it up.

203
00:24:00,086 --> 00:24:03,951
Well, the awakening balloon doesn't get tied up till we're fully liberated.

204
00:24:04,752 --> 00:24:07,757
So we've just got to keep blowing up that balloon.

205
00:24:09,121 --> 00:24:13,067
At various times of the day, we're not practicing formal meditation.

206
00:24:13,768 --> 00:24:15,611
Take the process of rising in the morning.

207
00:24:16,612 --> 00:24:21,078
As soon as we hear the bell and become aware of it, we immediately begin the noting.

208
00:24:22,080 --> 00:24:25,546
Hearing, hearing, aware of the process of hearing.

209
00:24:26,627 --> 00:24:29,111
And we are attentive to all the surrounding feelings.

210
00:24:29,711 --> 00:24:36,883
Tiredness, heaviness, depression, joy, interest, enthusiasm.

211
00:24:37,775 --> 00:24:40,623
we recognize all the surrounding thoughts that arise.

212
00:24:42,067 --> 00:24:45,536
Damn bell, oh hell, can't get up, I'm too exhausted.

213
00:24:46,377 --> 00:24:49,185
Bell, time to get up, quick, rush, rush, you'll be late.

214
00:24:50,368 --> 00:24:53,758
Bell, how wonderful, time to meditate.

215
00:24:55,071 --> 00:24:58,159
and we observe it all, noting it all as best we can.

216
00:24:59,039 --> 00:25:04,932
When finally a certain equanimity falls, we make our first intention, intending to rise.

217
00:25:05,875 --> 00:25:09,000
We pull back the bedclothes, pulling, pulling.

218
00:25:10,183 --> 00:25:13,991
But we also wear the feeling of the sheets, of the weight of the duvet.

219
00:25:15,102 --> 00:25:25,414
We're taking our time, noting and experiencing fully every movement, emotion and thought, using that noting to keep the mind steady on the object.

220
00:25:26,856 --> 00:25:37,650
Now don't be concerned if you can't get to this level for the first few days, but hopefully, with persistent effort, you'll experience this moment-to-moment mindfulness before too long.

221
00:25:38,895 --> 00:25:45,304
When it comes to the bathroom, there are obviously certain things we have to do at a normal speed, such as brushing our teeth.

222
00:25:46,065 --> 00:25:51,029
But even here we can slow down a little and become aware of all the intricate movements involved.

223
00:25:52,692 --> 00:25:58,618
We should become especially aware of that area around the necessary human activity, the calls of nature.

224
00:25:59,840 --> 00:26:01,343
Feeling the passing of water.

225
00:26:01,923 --> 00:26:05,627
Be aware of the thoughts and feelings surrounding the act.

226
00:26:05,647 --> 00:26:07,569
The same with the passing of stools.

227
00:26:08,494 --> 00:26:10,778
Normally our minds would prefer to be somewhere else.

228
00:26:11,598 --> 00:26:15,104
That's why we'll often stuff our toilets with holiday magazines.

229
00:26:16,445 --> 00:26:23,234
Well, this is an opportunity to find out how we really feel about those parts of our body that may disgust us.

230
00:26:24,416 --> 00:26:25,578
Is disgust necessary?

231
00:26:26,720 --> 00:26:33,169
A meditation course is a wonderful time to investigate the whole of our relationship to this body.

232
00:26:36,827 --> 00:26:38,631
Then there are meal times and tea breaks.

233
00:26:39,792 --> 00:26:42,777
And I shall go into this in more detail tomorrow morning.

234
00:26:43,519 --> 00:26:44,240
But it's the same.

235
00:26:44,820 --> 00:26:53,875
Noting and experiencing every intention and noting and experiencing every action, every feeling, every thought.

236
00:26:55,676 --> 00:26:59,020
Now you will have noticed that we are asked to note our intentions.

237
00:27:00,422 --> 00:27:05,067
Intentions play a crucial role in our psychology, according to the Buddha.

238
00:27:05,086 --> 00:27:10,713
They are thoughts laced with desire, both negative and positive, wanting and not wanting.

239
00:27:12,355 --> 00:27:20,284
These desires have all been conditioned by our past behavior, and the bulk of them have become habitual and barely conscious.

240
00:27:21,782 --> 00:27:28,535
How many of us are truly aware of our desire and intention to eat or sleep or talk to someone?

241
00:27:29,215 --> 00:27:31,759
We just find ourselves eating, sleeping and talking.

242
00:27:33,824 --> 00:27:44,382
All these habitual intentions have to be made quite conscious so that we can come to understand clearly how we ourselves are conditioning our own minds.

243
00:27:45,796 --> 00:27:59,079
And of course what we'll begin to do is to reinforce those habits that are good and skilful, such as eating for health's sake, but not reinforce those that do us harm, such as eating for greed.

244
00:28:00,680 --> 00:28:07,731
In this way, we can begin to take control of our lives and guide it towards the good, the beautiful and the happy.

245
00:28:08,933 --> 00:28:18,590
This self-knowledge concerning our intentions and their role in our lives is a very important part of the process of purifying the heart.

246
00:28:19,593 --> 00:28:24,882
So please do make a special effort to note intentions before doing anything.

247
00:28:27,207 --> 00:28:37,121
So, noting is a way to bring the thinking mind into the service of that higher consciousness, satipaṇya, awareness with intuitive intelligence.

248
00:28:38,462 --> 00:28:41,186
However, there is something a little more subtle going on.

249
00:28:42,669 --> 00:28:48,877
As soon as we use a word to point at something, it distances the object from that which knows.

250
00:28:50,056 --> 00:28:57,969
When a child shouts car, car, they're actually saying there's a car, there, over there, out there.

251
00:28:59,290 --> 00:29:01,054
The child is objectifying the world.

252
00:29:01,875 --> 00:29:03,718
It is detaching itself from the world.

253
00:29:05,240 --> 00:29:11,490
So what we're doing by pointing at all that we experience within us is to objectify the inner world.

254
00:29:12,712 --> 00:29:15,657
We are detaching ourselves from this inner world.

255
00:29:16,786 --> 00:29:19,313
We see it as if we were looking at a landscape.

256
00:29:20,256 --> 00:29:21,859
Only the landscape is within us.

257
00:29:22,742 --> 00:29:27,336
What Gerald Manley Hopkins, the poet, most happily called the inscape.

258
00:29:28,970 --> 00:29:33,857
Now, whenever we do that, we're experiencing in some little way the meaning of anatta.

259
00:29:35,019 --> 00:29:44,134
This is the doctrine that this body, these emotions, these thoughts, this personality doesn't constitute anything substantial.

260
00:29:45,336 --> 00:29:47,339
It's all made up of pieces and parts.

261
00:29:48,642 --> 00:29:56,074
And that there is some faculty within us that can stand above it and come to know these psychophysical phenomena for what they are.

262
00:29:57,251 --> 00:30:10,470
So noting something, naming it, allows that intelligence, paññā, to distance itself from the body, mind and heart and in so doing slowly comes to realize its own nature.

263
00:30:11,790 --> 00:30:23,547
In this way, noting becomes a very powerful tool to position that intelligent consciousness, satipaññā, so that it can come to realize the way things really are.

264
00:30:25,130 --> 00:30:28,608
Now there are three things that can go wrong with the noting technique.

265
00:30:30,337 --> 00:30:33,334
The first happens if we stop doing it deliberately.

266
00:30:34,563 --> 00:30:36,645
it then becomes like a background mantra.

267
00:30:37,827 --> 00:30:50,950
And you'll be surprised to find that when you go off onto a fantasy, to Tuscany or somewhere, on return to the meditation room, the mind is happily repeating, rising, falling, rising, falling.

268
00:30:51,932 --> 00:30:54,516
That's the amazing thing about the body-mind complex.

269
00:30:55,297 --> 00:30:56,779
It can be trained to do anything.

270
00:30:57,641 --> 00:30:59,845
Think of those concert performers.

271
00:30:59,825 --> 00:31:03,230
They're not directing their fingers, though they may be aware of them.

272
00:31:03,893 --> 00:31:07,338
They're using them to draw the sound they want out of the instrument.

273
00:31:08,181 --> 00:31:13,210
They play automatically, while the artist concentrates on feeling and expression.

274
00:31:15,349 --> 00:31:17,251
The second error is to become lazy.

275
00:31:18,093 --> 00:31:26,002
As soon as we stop putting right effort into the noting the whole thing begins to drop away and we start to lose the sharpness of the seeing.

276
00:31:27,085 --> 00:31:30,689
And often that laziness sits on the irritated dullness of boredom.

277
00:31:31,891 --> 00:31:33,211
Now beware of boredom.

278
00:31:33,932 --> 00:31:37,718
Boredom will always blame the practice for being boring.

279
00:31:38,659 --> 00:31:40,902
But what the wise meditator does

280
00:31:40,882 --> 00:31:49,538
is not to listen to boredom and give it any credence whatsoever, but to make that boredom, that subtle state, the object of meditation.

281
00:31:49,917 --> 00:32:01,219
They note boredom, boredom, while feeling the texture of boredom and losing their discomfort of being with the heart when it's in a bored state.

282
00:32:01,199 --> 00:32:06,644
Remember, as soon as we say to ourselves, I'm bored, well, we are bored.

283
00:32:07,425 --> 00:32:09,007
We've taken on that identity.

284
00:32:09,847 --> 00:32:10,548
So be careful.

285
00:32:11,009 --> 00:32:13,752
When boredom arises, see it for what it is.

286
00:32:14,212 --> 00:32:22,481
Yet another negative, unwholesome attitude that has to be noted, felt, observed, experienced and understood.

287
00:32:24,364 --> 00:32:26,987
And what is it that we come to understand about boredom?

288
00:32:27,659 --> 00:32:30,103
Well, the last thing we want to do is to appease it.

289
00:32:31,044 --> 00:32:42,823
Boredom tells us that if we don't want to get bored, we need distraction, we need a break, we need entertainment, we need a cup of tea, watch a bit of telly, call a friend and tell them how bored we are.

290
00:32:43,943 --> 00:32:46,607
Well, again, that's just playing into the hands of boredom.

291
00:32:47,470 --> 00:32:51,876
And do we really believe that distraction will satisfy boredom?

292
00:32:51,896 --> 00:32:52,738
Not at all.

293
00:32:53,461 --> 00:32:57,647
The more you feed boredom, paradoxically, the bigger boredom gets.

294
00:32:58,569 --> 00:33:00,292
Boredom feeds off distraction.

295
00:33:01,734 --> 00:33:09,048
No, the way to undermine boredom is to keep repeating what we are doing with added attention while feeling the boredom.

296
00:33:10,309 --> 00:33:17,982
We even turn upon the feeling of boredom itself and make that the object to be noted, felt, observed, experienced and understood.

297
00:33:19,869 --> 00:33:26,403
Boredom sits on the flames of expectation of something engrossing, anticipation of something exciting.

298
00:33:27,464 --> 00:33:29,548
One road to depression and Prozac.

299
00:33:30,991 --> 00:33:39,127
When through diligent practice, boredom begins to lose energy to our amazement, that energy turns into interest.

300
00:33:42,297 --> 00:33:45,962
The third mistake is to pay too much attention to the word itself.

301
00:33:47,125 --> 00:33:50,672
The word, remember, is there only to point the mind at the object.

302
00:33:51,393 --> 00:34:00,188
We're putting our attention onto the process of physical and mental feelings and thoughts, not onto the thought itself, the noting itself.

303
00:34:01,905 --> 00:34:05,509
Occasionally, a person finds the use of words intrusive.

304
00:34:06,471 --> 00:34:16,063
It's as though they can only hear and think of the word, and it seems an obstacle to any real contact with the feelings and sensations they're supposed to be experiencing.

305
00:34:17,605 --> 00:34:24,994
What this is showing to the meditator is how much they're experiencing the world through the medium of thought.

306
00:34:26,273 --> 00:34:42,431
By simply continuing to note, but with a clear intention to observe and experience sensations and feelings, this delusive way of experiencing the world will be slowly undermined and it will also correct the way we perceive the world.

307
00:34:43,333 --> 00:34:45,295
So it's worth persevering with.

308
00:34:46,777 --> 00:34:53,766
So noting should be done precisely as each object comes into the attention and it should be done deliberately.

309
00:34:56,242 --> 00:35:00,588
The next technique which is particular to the Mahasi method is to go slow.

310
00:35:01,809 --> 00:35:04,110
The body and mind work in total unison.

311
00:35:05,052 --> 00:35:07,534
Remember the Buddha said that it was like milk in water.

312
00:35:08,516 --> 00:35:09,577
The one affects the other.

313
00:35:10,277 --> 00:35:11,980
Sometimes the body affects the mind.

314
00:35:12,681 --> 00:35:16,143
When we get pain in the knees, we feel a mental discomfort as well.

315
00:35:17,184 --> 00:35:19,568
Sometimes the mind affects the body.

316
00:35:19,547 --> 00:35:22,393
When we feel depressed, the body feels heavy and dense.

317
00:35:23,534 --> 00:35:28,023
How well the body feels when we're in a state of joy or excitement.

318
00:35:30,288 --> 00:35:39,344
Now, if we slow the body down and do everything very slowly and deliberately, then this connection between the mind and the body will become very apparent.

319
00:35:40,556 --> 00:35:43,003
It affects the speed at which the mind is working.

320
00:35:44,106 --> 00:35:55,056
The slower the mind goes, the more clearly we perceive its workings, especially in that area where suffering is created, that whole area of desire, will and action.

321
00:35:56,385 --> 00:35:57,027
Take a film.

322
00:35:57,668 --> 00:36:00,452
The more you slow a film down, the more you can see.

323
00:36:00,512 --> 00:36:04,500
It's amazing to watch wildlife in slow motion.

324
00:36:05,260 --> 00:36:09,088
The balletic movements of a leopard in chase, usually just a blur.

325
00:36:10,210 --> 00:36:15,880
The flick of a frog's tongue as it catches a fly, usually we simply don't see it.

326
00:36:17,463 --> 00:36:21,427
but then we can actually stop a film and see things frame by frame.

327
00:36:22,568 --> 00:36:23,230
And did you know?

328
00:36:23,250 --> 00:36:27,514
A frog catches a fly underneath the tongue.

329
00:36:28,255 --> 00:36:28,936
Now there's something.

330
00:36:30,557 --> 00:36:39,268
In the same way, we find that as we go slower and slower, so many understandings will arise about how this human organism works.

331
00:36:39,585 --> 00:36:48,128
And because we are especially interested in this whole area of human suffering, we really begin to see how we get ourselves into a mess.

332
00:36:50,199 --> 00:36:53,304
Now you'll find that old habits easily assert themselves.

333
00:36:54,224 --> 00:37:01,373
If you find yourself rushing, rushing, rushing to eat, rushing to get to meditation on time, then stop.

334
00:37:01,954 --> 00:37:03,016
Take a deep breath.

335
00:37:03,896 --> 00:37:05,739
Get in touch with what's impelling you.

336
00:37:06,320 --> 00:37:10,706
Anxiety, worry, fear of embarrassment, or just pure habit, whatever.

337
00:37:11,567 --> 00:37:18,755
Talk to yourself and quieten the whole body down and wait till peace and equanimity have re-established themselves.

338
00:37:18,735 --> 00:37:22,061
Now one good trick is to do the action again.

339
00:37:22,842 --> 00:37:25,025
If you find yourselves rushing, then stop.

340
00:37:25,947 --> 00:37:31,456
Wait for calmness to return, go back to where you started, and begin again.

341
00:37:32,398 --> 00:37:36,003
And it's surprising how effective it is to do right what we do wrong.

342
00:37:37,164 --> 00:37:40,489
If you remember at school, we were always told to do our corrections.

343
00:37:40,971 --> 00:37:44,135
You see, our education wasn't that bad after all.

344
00:37:45,836 --> 00:37:48,684
Now take the simple and constant action of opening doors.

345
00:37:49,927 --> 00:37:53,356
Standing in front of a door, we make the intention to open it.

346
00:37:54,420 --> 00:37:57,007
We reach out, reaching, reaching.

347
00:37:57,989 --> 00:38:00,976
We touch the handle, touching, touching.

348
00:38:02,070 --> 00:38:05,916
experiencing just that sensual contact, the feel of metal.

349
00:38:06,976 --> 00:38:16,068
We turn the handle, feeling the resistance of the spring, turning, turning, applying the exact amount of pressure, and so on.

350
00:38:16,931 --> 00:38:20,275
Just think how many handles we've wrenched with oblivious cruelty.

351
00:38:21,757 --> 00:38:24,119
In this way, we communicate with the door.

352
00:38:26,422 --> 00:38:31,690
When it comes to how slow we should move around or do things, we can modulate our speed.

353
00:38:32,681 --> 00:38:36,545
In walking meditation, for instance, we can go fast for exercise.

354
00:38:37,907 --> 00:38:50,998
In the dining room, in the bathroom and other places where we share facilities and services, we need to be aware that other people are waiting, and we can move at a faster pace, perhaps even at a normal pace in certain circumstances.

355
00:38:52,518 --> 00:39:02,588
The important times to go very slow are towards the end of a walking period, so that we build up a maximum attention and concentration to bring into the sitting meditation.

356
00:39:03,157 --> 00:39:10,387
and any other action where we want to really microscope in on what is actually happening at the physical and mental bases.

357
00:39:11,568 --> 00:39:14,733
Mealtime, for instance, is an excellent opportunity to do this.

358
00:39:17,096 --> 00:39:22,802
Right at the start, we said that to become skilful we need to reflect on our experience.

359
00:39:22,822 --> 00:39:24,304
We need to acknowledge feedback.

360
00:39:25,306 --> 00:39:30,532
You'll see that after every sitting, I ask meditators to reflect on the experience of that hour.

361
00:39:31,777 --> 00:39:34,304
So we should every so often reflect on what's happening.

362
00:39:35,126 --> 00:39:38,614
And of course that's my job too, to reflect back to you how you're meditating.

363
00:39:39,577 --> 00:39:42,384
It's something I shall be constantly reminding you to do.

364
00:39:44,228 --> 00:39:48,960
However, there can arise here a confusion between being aware and being self-aware.

365
00:39:49,717 --> 00:39:53,420
We're not trying to be aware of ourselves practicing vipassana.

366
00:39:54,161 --> 00:39:58,126
We are simply being aware of anything that arises and passes away.

367
00:39:59,327 --> 00:40:02,831
We're not trying to be aware of ourselves doing things.

368
00:40:03,713 --> 00:40:06,235
We're trying just to be mindful doing things.

369
00:40:07,336 --> 00:40:10,521
If I'm washing the pots, I'm attentive to the actions.

370
00:40:11,240 --> 00:40:14,425
I'm not trying to be aware of myself washing pots.

371
00:40:15,079 --> 00:40:21,509
If, for instance, you try to be aware of yourself writing a letter or adding up a bill, you'll just get confused.

372
00:40:22,831 --> 00:40:25,014
Self-awareness will, of course, arise naturally.

373
00:40:25,474 --> 00:40:32,784
So note it, self-aware, self-aware, and then put your attention entirely on what you're actually doing.

374
00:40:36,172 --> 00:40:37,735
A final request.

375
00:40:38,896 --> 00:40:41,181
Please do not mix techniques.

376
00:40:42,041 --> 00:40:48,353
Give up for this period any other vipassana technique you've learnt or technique from another religion.

377
00:40:49,514 --> 00:40:57,387
Anything Tibetan, anything Hindu, yoga breathing, visualization, mantra, beading, bowing and so on.

378
00:40:58,648 --> 00:41:03,496
Judeo-Christian prayer and exercises can be put aside for a while too.

379
00:41:03,476 --> 00:41:04,918
why?

380
00:41:05,579 --> 00:41:31,829
firstly, it will confuse your practice secondly, it will confuse me and thirdly, you won't get the full benefit of what this course has to offer and for those of you who are new to this it will also mean that you will not know whether this form of meditation really suits you or not you've got to give it your all if you've any problems over this please talk to me about them at interview

381
00:41:31,809 --> 00:41:35,487
So again, please do not mix techniques.

382
00:41:37,557 --> 00:41:38,985
Let's pause here for a moment.

383
00:42:09,525 --> 00:42:17,815
So to recap, spiritual practice is utterly relentless and agonizingly repetitive.

384
00:42:17,835 --> 00:42:26,724
The purpose of our meditation course, and I prefer to call it a course and not a retreat for this reason, is to hone our skills of Vipassana meditation.

385
00:42:28,427 --> 00:42:36,916
The purpose of all these skills is to get consciousness to observe physical sensations, emotional feelings and thought objectively.

386
00:42:38,467 --> 00:42:47,385
The noting technique is used primarily to stop the mind thinking about things, stop the mind launching itself into thought and daydream.

387
00:42:48,887 --> 00:42:55,902
By noting diligently, we shall progress through the two stages of concentrated thought into pure vipassanā.

388
00:42:57,856 --> 00:43:09,751
Going slow has the purpose of centering us into this very moment and make us more and more aware of even the smallest movement of the body, heart and mind and how they are interrelated.

389
00:43:11,052 --> 00:43:15,197
And we need to become especially aware of intention and the role of intention.

390
00:43:17,820 --> 00:43:21,264
Now we ought to practice with sincere effort and great diligence.

391
00:43:22,375 --> 00:43:31,894
In the Satipatthana Sutta, the Discourse on Establishing Right Awareness, the Buddha uses the words ātāpī sampajāno satima.

392
00:43:33,077 --> 00:43:36,525
Satima means with awareness, with mindfulness.

393
00:43:37,385 --> 00:43:42,476
Sampajāno means with intuitive intelligence, with understanding.

394
00:43:42,456 --> 00:43:49,646
From these two words the compound satipanya has been formed which encapsulates the enlightened mind, the awakened mind.

395
00:43:50,628 --> 00:43:55,295
And atapi comes from tapo, which means heavy ascetic mortifications.

396
00:43:55,795 --> 00:44:03,105
Now that's the sort of commitment and energy the Buddha is asking us to put into the practice.

397
00:44:03,126 --> 00:44:07,130
The Buddha warns in the Dhammapada, a collection of verses.

398
00:44:07,550 --> 00:44:10,936
Vigilance is the path to the deathless.

399
00:44:11,936 --> 00:44:13,880
Negligence, the path to death.

400
00:44:15,163 --> 00:44:17,206
The heedful do not die.

401
00:44:17,246 --> 00:44:21,012
The heedless are as if already dead.

402
00:44:21,032 --> 00:44:24,818
Now, let's not be dead, heaven forbid.

403
00:44:25,519 --> 00:44:30,148
Let's be alive, alive with bright awareness and sharp intelligence.

404
00:44:31,764 --> 00:44:40,099
May your moment-to-moment vigilance and unshakable commitment to the practice bear you great fruit.

405
00:44:41,461 --> 00:44:50,719
May you be liberated from all suffering and attain the blissful freedom of Nibbana sooner rather than later.
